      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">Why Sports Words Work in Scrabble</h2>
      <p>Sports vocabulary has a unique advantage in Scrabble: many terms have crossed over from specialist jargon into everyday English. Words like BOGEY, RALLY, and TACKLE appear in standard dictionaries because they've been used figuratively for decades. A political "rally," a workplace "tackle," or a financial "bogey" — these metaphorical uses cement them in the lexicon.</p>

      <div class="not-prose my-6 grid grid-cols-1 sm:grid-cols-2 gap-4">
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-green-500/30 bg-green-950/10">
          <p class="text-green-400 font-semibold text-sm mb-1">✓ Valid in Scrabble</p>
          <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Generic sport terms: BOGEY, SCRUM, WICKET, DEUCE, VOLLEY, LUNGE, TACKLE, SPRINT, SERVE</p>
        </div>
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-red-500/30 bg-red-950/10">
          <p class="text-red-400 font-semibold text-sm mb-1">✗ Never Valid</p>
          <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Proper nouns: FIFA, NBA, Wimbledon, Lakers, Messi, Olympics, Premier League, Yankees</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <p>The distinction is simple: if the word exists as a common noun or verb in the dictionary independent of any specific team, league, or athlete, it's likely valid. CRICKET is valid (it's also an insect). TENNIS is valid (it's a generic game name). But WIMBLEDON is not — it's a proper noun referring to a specific place and tournament.</p>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">High-Value Sports Plays</h2>
      <p>The best sports words for scoring use premium consonants. K (5 points), J (8 points), W (4 points), and V (4 points) appear frequently in athletic terminology, making these words natural scorers without needing premium squares.</p>

      <div class="not-prose my-6 p-5 rounded-xl border border-blue-500/30 bg-blue-950/20">
        <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-blue-400 uppercase tracking-wider mb-2">💡 Key Insight</p>
        <p class="text-base text-gray-200">KAYAK uses <span class="text-white font-medium">two K tiles</span> (5 pts each) plus Y (4 pts) for 16 points from just 5 letters. That's 3.2 points per tile — exceptional efficiency without any premium square bonuses.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="not-prose my-6 flex flex-wrap items-center justify-center gap-3">
        <span class="inline-flex items-center gap-1.5 px-3 py-1.5 rounded-lg bg-gray-800 border border-gray-700 text-sm">
          <span class="text-white font-bold">KAYAK</span><span class="text-blue-400 text-xs">16 pts</span>
        </span>
        <span class="inline-flex items-center gap-1.5 px-3 py-1.5 rounded-lg bg-gray-800 border border-gray-700 text-sm">
          <span class="text-white font-bold">WICKET</span><span class="text-blue-400 text-xs">15 pts</span>
        </span>
        <span class="inline-flex items-center gap-1.5 px-3 py-1.5 rounded-lg bg-gray-800 border border-gray-700 text-sm">
          <span class="text-white font-bold">JOUST</span><span class="text-blue-400 text-xs">12 pts</span>
        </span>
        <span class="inline-flex items-center gap-1.5 px-3 py-1.5 rounded-lg bg-gray-800 border border-gray-700 text-sm">
          <span class="text-white font-bold">VOLLEY</span><span class="text-blue-400 text-xs">12 pts</span>
        </span>
        <span class="inline-flex items-center gap-1.5 px-3 py-1.5 rounded-lg bg-gray-800 border border-gray-700 text-sm">
          <span class="text-white font-bold">TACKLE</span><span class="text-blue-400 text-xs">12 pts</span>
        </span>
      </div>

      <p>JOUST is particularly interesting because J is worth 8 points — the second-highest tile value in Scrabble. In a tight board position where longer words won't fit, JOUST gives you 12 points in just 5 common letters. WICKET combines W (4 pts) and K (5 pts) for a powerful 15-point cricket term that most opponents won't challenge.</p>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">Sport-by-Sport Breakdown</h2>
      <p>Different sports contribute different types of words to the Scrabble dictionary. Golf alone gives us BOGEY, BIRDIE, BUNKER, and CADDY — all high-value plays. Tennis contributes DEUCE, RALLY, SERVE, and VOLLEY. Cricket offers WICKET, one of the highest-scoring sports terms available.</p>

      <div class="not-prose my-6 grid grid-cols-1 sm:grid-cols-2 gap-4">
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-amber-500/30 bg-amber-950/10">
          <p class="text-amber-400 font-semibold text-sm mb-1">⛳ Golf (4 words)</p>
          <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">BOGEY (9), BIRDIE (9), BUNKER (12), CADDY (11) — avg 10.3 pts</p>
        </div>
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-amber-500/30 bg-amber-950/10">
          <p class="text-amber-400 font-semibold text-sm mb-1">🎾 Tennis (4 words)</p>
          <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">DEUCE (8), RALLY (8), SERVE (8), VOLLEY (12) — avg 9.0 pts</p>
        </div>
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-amber-500/30 bg-amber-950/10">
          <p class="text-amber-400 font-semibold text-sm mb-1">🏏 Cricket (1 word)</p>
          <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">WICKET (15) — the highest-scoring single sport term</p>
        </div>
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-amber-500/30 bg-amber-950/10">
          <p class="text-amber-400 font-semibold text-sm mb-1">🏉 Rugby (1 word)</p>
          <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">SCRUM (9) — also used in agile software development</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">Strategy Tips for Sports Words</h2>

      <div class="not-prose my-6 grid grid-cols-1 gap-4">
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors">
          <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-purple-400 font-semibold">KAYAK on a DLS:</span> Place the first K on a Double Letter Score for 26 points total (K doubled to 10, plus remaining 11). On a Triple Letter Score, that's 31 points from a single 5-letter word.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors">
          <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-purple-400 font-semibold">JOUST for J dumps:</span> When J is stuck on your rack, JOUST uses common letters (O, U, S, T) that are usually available. It's far easier to play than JAZZ or JOCKEY.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors">
          <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-purple-400 font-semibold">Extend existing words:</span> SPRINT can become SPRINTED or SPRINTER for bingo potential. TACKLE extends to TACKLED or TACKLES. Adding -ED, -ER, -ING to sports words multiplies your scoring opportunities.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors">
          <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-purple-400 font-semibold">WICKET for double coverage:</span> At 6 letters with 15 points, WICKET is almost a bingo candidate. On a Triple Word Score, that's 45 points — game-changing territory from a word most players know.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors">
          <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-purple-400 font-semibold">Golf words cluster well:</span> BOGEY, BIRDIE, BUNKER, and CADDY all start with B or C — common rack letters. If you draw B+vowels, think golf first. BOGEY and BIRDIE both score 9 with very playable letters.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

